  "content": [
    {
      "card_id": "card-001",
      "idx": 0,
      "name": "to_go",
      "side_a": "To go (colloquial)",
      "side_b": "shàng",
      "side_c": "上",
      "side_d": "verb",
      "side_e": "Shàng nǎr qù? Wǒ shàng xuéxiào qù.",
      "side_f": "Where are you going? I'm going to school. (lit. 'up where go')",
      "side_g": "上 as a verb meaning 'to go to' is colloquial and usually pairs with a destination plus 去, as in 上哪儿去 or 上学校来. Distinct from 去, 上 implies heading toward somewhere familiar or routine, and it also appears in fixed expressions like 上课, 上班.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-002",
      "idx": 1,
      "name": "center",
      "side_a": "Center",
      "side_b": "zhōngxīn",
      "side_c": "中心",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Diànnǎo zhōngxīn lí túshūguǎn hěn jìn.",
      "side_f": "The computer center is very close to the library.",
      "side_g": "中心 means a functional hub or facility (电脑中心, 活动中心, 学生中心), not a geometric middle — use 中间 for 'in the middle of.' Commonly forms compounds like 市中心 (downtown) and 购物中心 (shopping center). Register is neutral and appears on signs everywhere.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-003",
      "idx": 2,
      "name": "to_hear_of",
      "side_a": "To be told; to hear of",
      "side_b": "tīngshuō",
      "side_c": "听说",
      "side_d": "verb",
      "side_e": "Tīngshuō huódòng zhōngxīn lǐbian yǒu kāfēi diàn.",
      "side_f": "I heard there's a coffee shop inside the activity center.",
      "side_g": "听说 typically starts a sentence to mark hearsay ('I heard that...') and cannot take a direct object like English 'hear' — for that use 听见 or 听到. Neutral register; often paired with a question tag 是吗 to confirm. Stronger evidential than 据说 in casual speech.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-004",
      "idx": 3,
      "name": "sports",
      "side_a": "Sports",
      "side_b": "yùndòng",
      "side_c": "运动",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Xià ge xīngqī yùndòngchǎng yǒu yùndòng huódòng.",
      "side_f": "Next week there's a sports event at the sports field.",
      "side_g": "运动 covers both 'sports' (noun) and 'to exercise' (verb: 我每天运动). It compounds freely: 运动场 (sports field), 运动员 (athlete), 运动会 (sports meet). Distinguish from 锻炼 which emphasizes the act of working out rather than the activity itself.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-005",
      "idx": 4,
      "name": "field",
      "side_a": "Field",
      "side_b": "chǎng",
      "side_c": "场",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Yùndòngchǎng jiù zài pángbiān.",
      "side_f": "The sports field is right next door.",
      "side_g": "场 is a bound morpheme meaning 'open ground/venue' and almost never stands alone — it needs a prefix: 运动场, 机场, 广场, 市场. Also a measure word for performances/games (一场电影, 一场比赛), where it's pronounced chǎng.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-006",
      "idx": 5,
      "name": "side",
      "side_a": "Side",
      "side_b": "pángbiān",
      "side_c": "旁边",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Kāfēi diàn jiù zài shūdiàn pángbiān.",
      "side_f": "The coffee shop is right beside the bookstore.",
      "side_g": "旁边 means 'next to / alongside' and typically follows the reference noun: X 旁边 ('beside X'), optionally with 的 before another noun. Interchangeable with 边上 in casual speech. Unlike 左边/右边, 旁边 doesn't specify which side.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-007",
      "idx": 6,
      "name": "far",
      "side_a": "Far",
      "side_b": "yuǎn",
      "side_c": "远",
      "side_d": "adjective",
      "side_e": "Shūdiàn lí zhèr yuǎn bu yuǎn?",
      "side_f": "Is the bookstore far from here?",
      "side_g": "远 is the standard adjective for physical distance and pairs canonically with 离: A 离 B 很远/不远. Can also be abstract (远亲, 长远). The A-not-A question form 远不远 is very common and natural. Opposite: 近.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-008",
      "idx": 7,
      "name": "away_from",
      "side_a": "Away from",
      "side_b": "lí",
      "side_c": "离",
      "side_d": "preposition",
      "side_e": "Diànnǎo zhōngxīn lí yùndòngchǎng bù yuǎn.",
      "side_f": "The computer center isn't far from the sports field.",
      "side_g": "离 is a preposition marking spatial/temporal distance between two points, and requires 远/近/不远/多远 or a concrete distance after the second noun: A 离 B + 远/近. Do not confuse with 从 (from a starting point of motion) — 离 is purely about gap, not departure. Also used for time: 离上课还有十分钟.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-009",
      "idx": 8,
      "name": "near",
      "side_a": "Near",
      "side_b": "jìn",
      "side_c": "近",
      "side_d": "adjective",
      "side_e": "Kāfēi diàn lí shūdiàn hěn jìn.",
      "side_f": "The coffee shop is very close to the bookstore.",
      "side_g": "近 functions just like 远 with 离: A 离 B 很近. Also means 'recent' or 'close (relationship)': 最近, 近几年, 亲近. In Beijing colloquial you'll hear 挺近的 often. Adverb 就 before a location verb emphasizes proximity: 就在旁边.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-010",
      "idx": 9,
      "name": "activity",
      "side_a": "Activity",
      "side_b": "huódòng",
      "side_c": "活动",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Xuéshēng huódòng zhōngxīn lǐbian yǒu hěn duō huódòng.",
      "side_f": "Inside the student activity center there are many activities. (lit. 'live-move')",
      "side_g": "活动 covers both 'activity/event' (noun) and 'to move around / exercise' (verb: 活动活动). As a noun, it's the go-to word for organized events — 参加活动, 举办活动. The character-by-character gloss 'live-move' hints at its dual sense.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-011",
      "idx": 10,
      "name": "middle",
      "side_a": "Middle",
      "side_b": "zhōngjiān",
      "side_c": "中间",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Diànnǎo zhōngxīn jiù zài túshūguǎn hé huódòng zhōngxīn zhōngjiān.",
      "side_f": "The computer center is right between the library and the activity center.",
      "side_g": "中间 means the literal middle/between, and the 'between A and B' pattern is A 和 B 中间 or A 跟 B 中间. Distinct from 中心 (a functional hub). Can also be temporal: 中间休息十分钟. Neutral tone on the second syllable.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-012",
      "idx": 11,
      "name": "bookstore",
      "side_a": "Bookstore",
      "side_b": "shūdiàn",
      "side_c": "书店",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Wǒ xiǎng shàng shūdiàn qù mǎi shū.",
      "side_f": "I want to go to the bookstore to buy books.",
      "side_g": "书店 is a standard compound: 书 (book) + 店 (shop). Note the broader 店 pattern: 商店, 饭店, 咖啡店, 书店. Mainland speakers prefer 书店; 书局 is more literary/older. 新华书店 is the famous state chain.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-013",
      "idx": 12,
      "name": "place",
      "side_a": "Place",
      "side_b": "dìfang",
      "side_c": "地方",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Shūdiàn zài shénme dìfang?",
      "side_f": "Where is the bookstore? (lit. 'what place')",
      "side_g": "地方 is a neutral, everyday noun for 'place/location,' and 什么地方 is a softer, more colloquial equivalent of 哪里/哪儿. Second syllable is toneless (dìfang). Also means 'local' as an adjective: 地方菜, 地方政府 — in which case it's dìfāng with full tone.",
      "level": 1
    },
    {
      "card_id": "card-014",
      "idx": 13,
      "name": "inside",
      "side_a": "Inside",
      "side_b": "lǐbian",
      "side_c": "里边",
      "side_d": "noun",
      "side_e": "Shūdiàn jiù zài huódòng zhōngxīn lǐbian.",
      "side_f": "The bookstore is right inside the activity center.",
      "side_g": "里边 means 'inside' and follows the reference noun: X 里边 ('inside X'). Interchangeable with 里面 (slightly more written) and 里头 (more northern/colloquial). The second syllable is neutral tone. Do not front it — *里边学校 is ungrammatical; say 学校里边.",
      "level": 1
    }
  ],
